🧠 Final Model Summary – Predicting Primary Pokémon Typing¶

After iterating through several modeling techniques, the most effective approach used a Multilayer Perceptron (MLP) to classify each Pokémon's primary typing based on engineered features from the dataset.

📁 Dataset Overview¶

  • Kaggle Pokemon Database: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mrdew25/pokemon-database
  • Total Pokémon used: 1,382 including alternate forms, or 1,054 base forms only
  • Target variable: Primary Type
    • Type classification: Multiclass (18 possible labels)

🧪 Features Used¶

  • Total: 858 after preprocessing
  • Raw stats: Health, Attack, Defense, Sp. Attack, Sp. Defense, Speed
  • Composite stat: Base Stat Total
  • Normalized stats (each stat as a % of total): (Base Stat / Base Stat Total) * 100
  • Categorical traits: Primary/Secondary Egg Groups, Primary Ability, Classification
  • Boolean flag: is_pre_evolution (whether the Pokémon has a pre-evo)

✅ Model Overview¶

  • Model: MLPClassifier (Neural Network)
  • Architecture: 2 hidden layers with 256 and 128 neurons respectively
  • Training Strategy: 80/20 stratified train-test split
  • Loss Optimization: Backpropagation with gradient descent (max_iter=500)
  • Evaluation Metric: [Kappa]

📊 Results¶

  • Kappa Score: 0.724
  • Accuracy: 74% on the test set (277 samples)
  • Class coverage: All 18 types included, with strongest results on Normal, Water, Psychic, Grass, Fire, and Poison types
  • Challenging classes: Ice, Dark, and Fighting showed lower recall

🔍 Feature Insights (via Permutation Importance)¶

Top predictors:

  • In MLP the top 15 features were all abilities
  • In RF and KNN top 15 features were primarily base stats

⚠️ Features That Hurt or Had No Impact¶

  • Over-engineered features like Attack - Defense and Attack / Defense consistently lowered Kappa when added to the feature set
  • These interaction features either:
    • Introduced noise
    • Added redundancy (since both original stats were already included)
  • Hidden Ability was tested as a feature but had no measurable impact on performance and was dropped
    • This may be due to it being either missing, poorly populated, or not well-aligned with type logic
  • PCA on stats showed interesting visual structure, but replacing or adding raw stats with PCA components led to a significant drop in performance, in both MLP and RF but helped KNN

🎯 Key Takeaways¶

  • Neural networks (MLP) outperformed traditional classifiers like Random Forests (Kappa = 0.72 vs .63).
  • Stratified splitting + simple feature engineering were critical to success (PCA produced worst results).
  • Oversampling and class weighting provided no improvements and hurt performance, showing that the original features were already strong.
  • Including alternate forms meaningfully improves model accuracy and Kappa when using MLPs but decreases these values in RF.
  • MLPClassifier gave the best balance of generalization and class performance for a multiclass prediction problem with 18 target labels.
